Hubei Province, the country's sixth-largest producer of poultry eggs, is suffering a severe test of its farming industry.

The full text is 3187 words and takes about 6 minutes to read

"There are about 10 million laying hens in Xinzhou, and only two hundred thousand per day. Some farmers only have two or three days left to feed them, " said Ma Xinhui, president of the Poultry Industry Association in Xinzhou District of Wuhan, "My own feed will only last another ten days and a half months. "

A farmer receives a reporter to interview a telephone to chat in a hurry a few words to hang up, "excuse me I am waiting for a feed factory telephone. "

Liu Yuntao, secretary of the Hubei Poultry Industry Association, said similar difficulties were common among farmers not only in Wuhan but across Hubei Province. On Jan. 28, the Hubei Provincial Poultry Association sent letters to the two state owned enterprises, asking them to support each other with 18,000 tons of corn and 12,000 tons of soybean meal to tide them over.

He Nianhua, head of the Animal Husbandry and Veterinary Department of the Hubei Agricultural and Rural Department, told reporters that on January 31, the Hubei Provincial Headquarters for the prevention and control of the new type of pneumonia has issued the following request to ensure the smooth transportation of feed, veterinary drugs, meat, eggs, milk and vegetables, but "there may be a process of Implementation" .

━━━━━

100,000 hens could be lost as soon as farmers run out of food. Four million will be lost

Ma's farm has 150,000 layers and produces one hundred thousand eggs a day. His eggs sold to Wuhan's Shangchao, every day by the Shangchao transport vehicles to haul goods, "I personally temporarily do not worry about sales, and sometimes to help take a bit. "

Mei Xinwang, who also runs a farm in the Xinzhou district, was not so lucky. Before his layers sold to many provinces across the country, now it is "can not find cars, no one to pick up, the new year has not shipped. ". The farm, which produces more than 200 crates of 100,000 hens a day, 360 a carton, is already filling up his warehouse, "in two or three days at most. "

"There are very few cars that can walk now, only the 'vegetable basket' cars can walk, and the surplus production capacity can not be transported out, " Ma Xinhui said. And as a big egg province, Hubei's eggs are sold to all parts of the country, "It is estimated that 70 percent is exported, " he said. But in the epidemic situation, traffic control measures in many parts of Hubei have made it difficult for transport vehicles to move, "from Xinzhou to downtown Wuhan is very difficult. "

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The Hubei Poultry Association is asking for emergency assistance. Image courtesy of the web

Hubei Province raises about 170 million laying hens all year round, making Hubei the second leading industry in animal husbandry after pig farming, with poultry and egg production ranking sixth in the country, according to an article on the website of the Hubei Provincial Department of Agriculture and Rural Affairs. In 2018, Hubei Province produced 1.7153 million tons of poultry eggs, 4.3095 million tons of meat and 380,000 people in the animal husbandry industry, according to Statistics Bureau.

"There are also a conservative estimate of 120 million laying hens, and the egg production rate is 90 percent, with more than 100 million eggs being produced every day, " said Du Jinping, a researcher at the Animal Husbandry and Veterinary Research Institute of the Hubei Academy of Agricultural Sciences, "There are still quite a few layers that were previously used for poverty alleviation, and poor households are less able to withstand risks. "

Eggs can not be sold may also be temporarily stored, Du Jinping and a number of farmers told reporters that the current weather conditions, in the warehouse can also be stored for 7 to 14 days.

A more pressing problem is the lack of feed. Mei Xinwang managed to pull in a batch of feed yesterday, but "it won't last two days, " she said, adding that it would cost about 40 yuan to raise each chicken from a young plant to lay eggs, and 100,000 layers would starve to death, "The loss is four million per cent and all the investment is gone. "

Liu Yuntao, the secretariat of the Hubei Poultry Industry Association, told reporters that in addition to the difficulties in selling eggs, lack of feed such as corn and soybean meal, it is also difficult for young chickens, which are used as raw materials for the production of layers and broilers, to go on the road, and it is difficult for packages such as egg trays to be imported, problems such as difficulty in hauling chicken manure.

According to Ma Xinhui's knowledge, there are two chicken seedling factories that produce 130,000 and 30,000 chicken seedlings each day. "If you can't transport them out, you have to bury them alive. " Du said that two batches of 100,000 chicken seedlings have been buried in photographs sent by a chicken seedling factory, "Now the chicks are selling for $5.50-$7 each, which is a one hundred thousand per cent loss. "

At present, there is no effect on the breeding of layers, but Ma Xinhui estimated that if the seedlings can not keep up now, three months after the impact on egg production will be relatively large.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Burying of chicken seedlings and discarded eggs during incubation in poultry farms. Photo courtesy of the respondents

The roads in and out of the province are not smooth, and the transportation of feed and agricultural products is difficult

Liu said one of the main reasons for the problems was poor roads.

One is that roads in Hubei Province are hard to get through. Similar traffic controls have been introduced across Wuhan since it closed the Han corridor on January 23, and even within the city there are restrictions on roads. For example, young chicks are considered "live birds" that are not allowed on the road, Du said. "In the industry, young chicks and young ducks that have just come out of the shell are considered 'raw materials for production, ' and adult chickens sent to slaughter are called 'live birds. ' "

Some farmers have learned that as long as the local animal husbandry department to apply for a pass, there will be no problem with cargo transportation. But Liu received a response from farmers said: "One day the vehicle transport certificate can be opened, the next day can not open, told the truck can pass, do not need to prove, in fact, no proof inch by inch. "

This is what happened to Mei Xinwang. Because the farm is short of food, on January 31, he prepared to run to the feed factory to pull feed, road checkpoint was stopped. He called the mayor hotline, the new pneumonia prevention and control headquarters in Hubei Province, Hubei Provincial Public Security Department to report the situation. About two hours, after the coordination of various departments, his vehicle can finally be released, pulled back to the emergency feed. On February 1st, however, he was stopped again while trying to pull the feed.

"Even if we can get out of the feed mill or the chicken FRY factory here, we may still encounter difficulties getting off the expressway or into the village, " Du said.

Second, Hubei Province and the outside world traffic also appeared a lot of trouble. Liu Yuntao said that many foreign drivers do not want to come to Hubei. "They need to be isolated for 14 days after they go back. " Even if the feed is brought in, Du said, they want to go out again, "It may be regulated by another policy. If you can't get out of the car or the people, you don't want to come. "

Feed is also transported by water. Liu Yuntao said that at present, the dock is closed, loading and unloading cargo difficulties. Du Jinping also learned that some bulk feed "in the Yangtze River estuary blocked, or not under the pier. "

And Mei Xinwang contact many feed manufacturers, or even directly because of the epidemic situation and stopped work, "the local government does not allow to start. "

Du suggested that poultry farmers could use a "forced molting" technique in production to reduce feed consumption in the short term, "but there is no way to do it, and it is also very costly for farmers. "

"whenever there is an outbreak, the poultry industry is the first to be hit, and trade and circulation are restricted, which is very detrimental to farming, " Du said.

Hubei Provincial Department of Agriculture and rural areas: the General Headquarters has the following guarantee transportation

On January 30, the Ministry of Agriculture and rural areas, the Ministry of Ministry of Transport of the People's Republic of China and the Ministry of Public Security issued a joint statement calling on all localities to "strictly implement the 'green passage' system" and "ensure the smooth transportation of fresh and live agricultural products"  "ensure the normal circulation of 'vegetable basket' products and agricultural Means of production. "

In fact, on January 27, before the Central Ministry issued the document, the Hubei Provincial Department of Agriculture and rural areas had already issued the document, calling for "effectively unblocking channels for the transfer of urgently needed materials such as vegetables and feed. ".

An "emergency response report" stamped with the official seal of the Hubei Pig Industry Association said that the above-mentioned document of the Hubei Provincial Department of Agriculture and rural areas "is a blessing for our province's breeding enterprises! " But in the process of implementation, "There are still difficulties with multi-sector management, unclear responsibilities, changes in filing policies and so on. "

"The policies are all good policies, " Ma said. "But now we can't move. "

Wuhan is the most restrictive in this area, but outside Wuhan, "The feed and eggs are almost ready to move, " he said, noting that a shipment of day-old chicks had been delivered to Hong Lake. "Some districts and counties are flexible enough to get permits, and in other places, the Department of Agriculture and animal husbandry is coordinating. ".

Both Ma and DU understand that under the current epidemic prevention situation, the government needs to consider all aspects of the balance.

"sometimes it makes sense, " Ma said. "All over the world, all walks of life have big losses. It's not your family's business. ".

"Wuhan in Hubei Province is the center of the epidemic, and it's understandable that people are so big, " Du said. "But people have to eat, right? I hope we can consider these issues at an appropriate time. "

February 1, Wuhan Agricultural and Rural Bureau of Animal Husbandry and veterinary staff told reporters that over the past few days, has coordinated a number of farmers transport problems, sales issues are also in contact with the Commerce Department to coordinate, at the same time is to apply for relevant subsidies to the financial sector, to consider compensation farmers, poultry farms losses. However, the staff member said that at present only to help coordinate the resolution of specific farmers reflected the specific difficulties of the aquaculture industry has not been addressed as a whole.

He Nianhua, director of Animal Husbandry and Veterinary Department of Hubei Agricultural and Rural Department, told reporters that the new type of pneumonia prevention and control headquarters of Hubei Province has been ordered to ensure the smooth transportation of feed, veterinary medicine, meat, eggs, milk and vegetables. "previous circulars issued by the agricultural authorities may not be implemented properly under the epidemic prevention situation. The Provincial General Administration of Health and Prevention has already issued the following circulars yesterday, and some places have already started to pass them in succession today. Implementation may be a process, " he said.

At present, the seedlings are still regarded as "live poultry" , and wild animals, dangerous goods together as not allowed on the road control of goods. He said that the source and route of transmission of the new pneumonia were not yet clear, and that "it is not wrong to take more severe measures. " Accordingly, livestock such as pigs and live poultry, which are the sources of "meat, " Transport to the slaughterhouse is not easy, he said.

"Right now we are working on it, maybe waiting for the situation to stabilize a little bit before relaxing the controls, " he said. "Our solutions are dynamic, and we are keeping up with the latest changes every day. "
